<secrets_in_frontend_guide>
<title>SECRETS IN FRONTEND (Client-Side Exposure)</title>

<critical>Frontend applications frequently leak sensitive credentials through JavaScript bundles, source maps, environment files, localStorage, and hardcoded values. Unlike backend secrets, frontend code is fully accessible to users. Focus on static analysis of JS bundles, source map extraction, storage API inspection, and mobile app binary analysis.</critical>

<scope>
- JavaScript bundle analysis (webpack, vite, parcel)
- Source map secret extraction (.js.map files)
- .env file exposure and embedded values
- Hardcoded API keys in SPAs (React, Vue, Angular)
- localStorage/sessionStorage/IndexedDB secrets
- Service worker credential leakage
- Mobile app embedded secrets (APK, IPA inspection)
- GraphQL/REST client hardcoded tokens
- Firebase, AWS Cognito, Auth0 client secrets
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Enumerate JS assets: find all .js files, check for .map files, identify frameworks
2. Download and analyze bundles: search for API keys, tokens, passwords patterns
3. Extract source maps: reconstruct original source code from production bundles
4. Inspect browser storage: localStorage, sessionStorage, IndexedDB, cookies
5. Monitor network traffic: capture API keys in headers, query parameters
6. Decompile mobile apps: extract strings, configs, embedded credentials
7. Test discovered secrets: validate they grant unauthorized access
8. Assess impact: scope of access, privilege level, data exposure
</methodology>

<javascript_bundle_analysis>
<discovery>
- View page source: <script src="/static/js/main.abc123.js">
- Browser DevTools: Sources tab → all loaded scripts
- Network tab: filter by JS, find all .js files
- Sitemap/robots.txt: may reference JS files
- Webpack stats.json: metadata about all chunks
</discovery>

<secret_patterns>
Regular expressions for common secrets:
- API keys: /[a-zA-Z0-9_-]{32,}/g, /AIza[0-9A-Za-z-_]{35}/
- AWS keys: /AKIA[0-9A-Z]{16}/, /[0-9a-zA-Z/+=]{40}/
- JWT: /eyJ[a-zA-Z0-9_-]*\.eyJ[a-zA-Z0-9_-]*\.[a-zA-Z0-9_-]*/
- Private keys: /-----BEGIN (RSA|EC|OPENSSH) PRIVATE KEY-----/
- Stripe: /sk_live_[a-zA-Z0-9]{24,}/, /pk_live_[a-zA-Z0-9]{24,}/
- Firebase: /AIza[0-9A-Za-z-_]{35}/, firebaseConfig objects
- Slack: /xox[baprs]-[0-9a-zA-Z-]{10,48}/
- GitHub: /ghp_[a-zA-Z0-9]{36}/

Search for variable names:
- API_KEY, API_SECRET, SECRET_KEY, PRIVATE_KEY
- TOKEN, ACCESS_TOKEN, AUTH_TOKEN
- PASSWORD, PASSWD, PWD
- CLIENT_SECRET, APP_SECRET
</secret_patterns>

<bundle_extraction_tools>
- wget/curl: download all JS files
  wget -r -l1 -H -t1 -nd -N -np -A.js,.map https://target.com/
- Online beautifiers: de-minify obfuscated code
  - JSBeautifier, Prettier
- Automated scanners:
  - truffleHog, gitleaks, detect-secrets
  - grep, ripgrep for pattern matching
</bundle_extraction_tools>

<framework_specific>
<react>
- process.env.REACT_APP_* embedded at build time
- Check for REACT_APP_API_KEY, REACT_APP_SECRET
- .env file patterns exposed in bundle
</react>

<vue>
- process.env.VUE_APP_* embedded
- vuex store may contain secrets
- Inspect window.__INITIAL_STATE__
</vue>

<angular>
- environment.ts compiled into bundles
- Check window.ng.probe() for component state
- Angular services may expose config
</angular>

<nextjs>
- NEXT_PUBLIC_* variables exposed
- Check /_next/static/chunks/ for secrets
- getServerSideProps data in __NEXT_DATA__
</nextjs>
</framework_specific>
</javascript_bundle_analysis>

<source_map_extraction>
<finding_source_maps>
- Check for .map files: main.js.map, vendors.js.map
- sourceMappingURL comment in JS files:
  //# sourceMappingURL=main.js.map
- Common paths:
  /static/js/*.js.map
  /_next/static/chunks/*.js.map
  /assets/*.js.map
  /dist/*.js.map
- Try appending .map to any .js file
</finding_source_maps>

<extracting_source_code>
- Source maps contain original source code
- Use source-map library or online tools
- Reconstruct directory structure from sources array
- Search reconstructed code for secrets (easier than minified)

Example:
{
  "version": 3,
  "sources": ["src/config/api.js", "src/utils/auth.js"],
  "sourcesContent": ["const API_KEY = 'sk_live_abc123...'", ...]
}
</extracting_source_code>

<high_value_files>
- config.js, constants.js, api.js
- auth.js, authentication.js
- services/api.js, services/http.js
- .env.local, .env.production (if leaked)
- firebase.js, aws-exports.js
</high_value_files>
</source_map_extraction>

<browser_storage_inspection>
<localstorage_sessionstorage>
- Open DevTools → Application → Storage
- Look for keys: token, access_token, api_key, jwt, session
- Extract values: localStorage.getItem('token')
- Secrets may be base64 encoded or JSON stringified

Common patterns:
- auth_token, authentication_token
- user (may contain admin flags, tokens)
- config, settings (may contain API keys)
- cache (GraphQL clients cache responses with sensitive data)
</localstorage_sessionstorage>

<indexeddb>
- More complex storage, often used by PWAs
- DevTools → Application → IndexedDB
- Inspect object stores for credentials
- Apollo GraphQL, Redux persist may store tokens here
</indexeddb>

<cookies>
- Check for httpOnly=false cookies with tokens
- Session cookies accessible to JavaScript
- Inspect document.cookie in console
- CSRF tokens, JWT in cookies
</cookies>

<service_workers>
- Check /sw.js, /service-worker.js
- May cache API responses with secrets
- Inspect cache storage in DevTools
- Offline functionality may persist tokens
</service_workers>
</browser_storage_inspection>

<environment_files>
<dotenv_exposure>
- .env, .env.local, .env.production
- Common paths:
  /.env
  /public/.env
  /static/.env
  /.env.local
- May be served if misconfigured web server

Contents:
API_KEY=sk_live_abc123
DATABASE_URL=postgres://user:pass@host/db
AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=AKIA...
JWT_SECRET=super-secret-key
</dotenv_exposure>

<config_files_exposure>
- config.json, appsettings.json
- aws-exports.js (AWS Amplify)
- firebase-config.js
- google-services.json (Android), GoogleService-Info.plist (iOS)
</config_files_exposure>
</environment_files>

<mobile_app_secrets>
<android_apk>
- Download APK from Play Store or device
- Unzip APK (it's a ZIP archive)
- Inspect resources:
  - res/values/strings.xml (hardcoded strings)
  - assets/ folder (config files)
  - AndroidManifest.xml (API keys in meta-data)
- Decompile with jadx, apktool:
  jadx -d output app.apk
  grep -r "api_key\|API_KEY\|secret" output/
- Native libraries (.so files):
  strings lib/arm64-v8a/libnative.so | grep -i key
</android_apk>

<ios_ipa>
- Extract IPA (ZIP archive)
- Payload/App.app/ contains resources
- Info.plist: keys, URL schemes
- embedded.mobileprovision
- Binary analysis with class-dump, Hopper
- Inspect bundled files: config.plist, settings.json
- strings App.app/App | grep -E 'api|key|secret'
</ios_ipa>

<react_native_expo>
- JavaScript bundle in APK/IPA
- Inspect index.android.bundle, main.jsbundle
- Same techniques as web JS analysis
- Expo manifest contains sensitive config
</react_native_expo>
</mobile_app_secrets>

<third_party_integrations>
<firebase>
- firebaseConfig object in JS:
{
  apiKey: "AIza...",
  authDomain: "app.firebaseapp.com",
  projectId: "project-id",
  storageBucket: "...",
  messagingSenderId: "...",
  appId: "..."
}
- API key is public but check Firebase security rules
- Test unauthorized access: read/write Firestore, Storage
</firebase>

<aws_cognito>
- aws-exports.js from AWS Amplify
- Contains user pool IDs, identity pool IDs
- Client secrets if misconfigured (should not be in frontend)
- Test with AWS SDK to enumerate users, data
</aws_cognito>

<auth0>
- domain, clientId, audience in config
- Client secret should NOT be in frontend
- Check if secret is leaked (enables impersonation)
</auth0>

<stripe>
- Publishable key (pk_live_*) is safe
- Secret key (sk_live_*) is CRITICAL—full account access
- Webhook secrets (whsec_*) enable event forgery
</stripe>

<google_maps_cloud>
- API keys with insufficient restrictions
- Test if key allows unrestricted API access
- Check for billing fraud potential
</google_maps_cloud>
</third_party_integrations>

<graphql_clients>
<apollo_client>
- Check cache in localStorage/IndexedDB
- apollo-cache-persist stores full cache
- May contain query results with PII, tokens
- Inspect window.__APOLLO_STATE__
</apollo_client>

<relay>
- Relay store in memory and persisted
- Check for sensitive data in cached responses
</relay>

<hardcoded_tokens>
- Authorization headers in client code:
  headers: { 'Authorization': 'Bearer hardcoded_token' }
- Admin/debug endpoints with hardcoded credentials
- Test accounts with known passwords
</hardcoded_tokens>
</graphql_clients>

<validation>
1. Prove secret existence: show exact location in bundle or storage
2. Extract secret value: copy full token/key/password
3. Test functionality: demonstrate secret grants access
4. Scope impact: what data/actions does secret enable
5. Check expiration: is secret still valid (not rotated)
6. Verify sensitivity: confirm it's not a public/safe value
7. Document all instances: search for multiple occurrences
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Public API keys (intended for client-side: Google Maps publishable, Stripe pk_)
- Demo/test keys for development (not production)
- Redacted secrets (dots, asterisks) in code comments
- Public OAuth client IDs (safe unless secret also leaked)
- Encrypted/encoded values without decryption key
- Public configuration values (non-sensitive settings)
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Full API access if admin/privileged keys leaked
- Authentication bypass if JWT secrets exposed
- Database access if connection strings leaked
- Cloud resource access (AWS, GCP, Azure credentials)
- Third-party service abuse (Stripe, Twilio, SendGrid)
- User impersonation if auth tokens exposed
- Data exfiltration from backend services
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always check for .map files—they contain original source with clearer variable names
2. Search for "key", "secret", "token", "password" case-insensitively in all JS
3. Don't ignore mobile apps—APKs/IPAs often have hardcoded secrets
4. localStorage inspection is quick win—tokens often stored client-side
5. Firebase apiKey is public but check security rules (real vulnerability)
6. Source maps may be disabled in prod but check staging/dev environments
7. Use automated tools first (truffleHog, gitleaks) then manual review
8. Check git history—secrets may have been removed but remain in commit history
9. Test discovered secrets immediately—they may be rotated quickly
10. Document exact bundle URL and line number for reproduction
11. React/Vue devtools can expose component state with secrets
12. Service workers cache may persist long after frontend update
</pro_tips>

<remember>Frontend code is public—all secrets exposed client-side are compromised. Never embed sensitive credentials in JavaScript bundles, source maps, or browser storage. Use backend proxies, secure token exchange, and rotate any leaked secrets immediately.</remember>
</secrets_in_frontend_guide>
